Most parts of the country will continue to receive minimal rainfall with an exception of a few despite a flooding warning issued last month, the Meteorological Department has forecasted. Counties set to experience showers include Nyeri, Murangâ€™a, Kirinyaga, Embu, Meru, Kiambu, Tharaka Nithi, Laikipia, Nyandarua and Nairobi. In Western Kenya, Rift Valley and Nyanza there will be marginal rainfall in Kakamega, Vihiga, Busia, Bungoma, Kisumu, Kisii, Siaya, Homa Bay, Kericho, Nandi, Bomet, Nakuru, West Pokot, Elgeyo-Marakwet, Baringo, Uasin Gishu, Trans Nzoia and Narok. The department, however, did not rule out flooding and urged National Disaster Management Unit to be alert to mitigate any calamity that may arise as a result of heavy rains. Poor sanitation Pastoralists and fishermen in Turkana county have been warned of possible flash floods this week, with areas around the Lake Turkana set to experience heavy rains. Kenya Meteorological Department acting director Stella Aura cautioned Kenyans to be on the lookout for flooding and outbreak of waterborne diseases, especially in areas with poor sanitation and drainage systems. Last month, the weatherman had warned Kenyans to brace for heavy rainfall and flooding. Aura attributed the erratic weather to global warning.